  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me in Bari. As a delivery driver with a vocational diploma and three kids, I've never had the chance to dive deep into academic fields, but I've noticed how students from working-class backgrounds, especially those who don't fit the 'typical' STEM profile, often feel pressure when they're told they're 'not cut out' for science or math. It's not about intelligence—it's about the fear of confirming a stereotype that they're less capable. When a kid from a family with no formal education gets labeled 'not good at math,' it's a real psychological burden. I've seen it in my own community, where kids who want to learn but feel stuck because of their background end up giving up early. This isn't just about individual failure—it's systemic. We need to address it by creating environments where everyone feels safe to try, not just the ones who already fit the mold. In Bari, where I grew up, we have schools that could use more support for students who don't have the same resources as their peers. My depression sometimes makes me feel like I'm not good enough, and I've realized that stereotype threat can make people feel that way even more. So yes, we absolutely need to address it—by changing how we talk about STEM, making it accessible to all, and ensuring that no one feels like they're being judged before they even start. It's not about fixing people; it's about fixing the system that makes them feel like they don't belong.",
